message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The physical changes are consistent with physiological development, which is expected in girls at around ages 8-13. Hamartoma of the hypothalamus can cause precocious puberty, but the patient’s physical changes are consistent with normal puberty. Mosaic G-protein mutation can cause McCune-Albright syndrome, which can also cause precocious puberty, but there are no other symptoms consistent with this condition. A functioning follicular ovarian cyst can secrete hormones that may lead to abnormal uterine bleeding, but it is not likely to cause the physical changes described in this patient.
